NAME triple-pass-protocol
PURPOSE
Copy mistakes compound. A wrong tone in one post doesn't just affect that post — it drifts the brand. This protocol catches voice errors, weak headlines, and psychological framing issues before they reach Stark or go public. 
--- 
THE THREE PASSES
PASS 1 — GENERATE
WRITE_THE_FULL_COPY_OUTPUT hooks, body, CTAs, hashtags. Don't self-edit during generation — complete the output first.
PASS 2 — CRITIQUE (ADVERSARIAL)
Stop. Read the copy as if you've never seen the brand before. Ask every question on this list: 
Voice check: 
Is this unmistakably NO Hourbour — or could it belong to any brand? Does the tone match exactly? (Novizio: editorial, self-assured. Hourbour: plain English, trustworthy) Are there any banned words for this venture? (Novizio: affordable, cheap; Hourbour: complicated, risky) Any exclamation marks in Novizio body copy? Remove them. 
Headline quality: 
Did I write 5 headlines before choosing 1, or did I settle for the first? Does the headline earn the next line, or is it vague enough to ignore? Would a reader who doesn't know the brand still find this worth reading? 
Every word earns its place: 
Read back slowly. Mark every word that doesn't add meaning. Remove them. Are there filler phrases? ("In today's world", "We're excited to share", "Don't miss out") IT CTA specific? ("Start your free trial" "Learn more") 
Kahneman check (mandatory before flagging to Stark): 
What psychological frame is this copy using? Is it intentional? ITre conflicting framing in the same piece? (loss aversion + social proof without coherence) Would this pass System 1 — does it feel right immediately, not just on analysis? 
PASS 3 — FIX
Rewrite anything that failed Pass 2. Do not rationalize tone drift. If it doesn't sound like the venture, rewrite — don't leave it. 
--- 
OUTPUT RULE
Stark sees the Pass 3 output only. Never narrate the triple-pass process. 